QUIZ 2 - FOR LECTURE 3.


ANSWERS (for explanation, see pdf of answers)
1. Mean 
2. The probability of observing the data given that the null hypothesis is true.
3. The spread of values around the mean.
4. Correlation measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between variables.
5. (Data point - Mean) / Standard Deviation.
6. 0.05



QUESTIONS
1.
What is the measure of central tendency that is most influenced by outliers?
Mean
Median
Mode
Standard Deviation

2.
What is the p-value in hypothesis testing?
The probability of making a Type I error
The probability of making a Type II error
The level of significance for the test
The probability of observing the data given that the null hypothesis is true

3.
What is the standard deviation?
The average value in a dataset
The spread of values around the mean
The middle value in a dataset
The most frequently occurring value in a dataset

4.
What is the difference between correlation and causation?
Correlation indicates a cause-and-effect relationship between variables.
Causation indicates a strong association between variables.
Correlation measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between variables.
Causation measures the statistical significance of the relationship between variables

5.
What is the formula for calculating the z-score of a data point?
(Data point - Mean) / Standard Deviation
(Data point - Median) / Interquartile Range
(Data point - Mode) / Range
(Data point - Mean) / Range

6.
What is the p-value threshold commonly used for statistical significance?
0.05
0.10
0.01
0.001

